SIMPLE: surfeit
RECORDS: 3

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Surfeit
<hw>Sur"feit</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>surfet</ets>, OF. <ets>surfait</ets>, <ets>sorfait</ets>, excess,
arrogance, crime, fr. <ets>surfaire</ets>, <ets>sorfaire</ets>, to
augment, exaggerate, F. <ets>surfaire</ets> to overcharge;
<ets>sur</ets> over + <ets>faire</ets> to make, do, L.
<ets>facere</ets>. See <er>Sur-</er>, and <er>Fact</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>Excess in eating and drinking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Let not Sir <qex>Surfeit</qex> sit at thy board.</q>
<rj><qau>Piers Plowman.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Now comes the sick hour that his <qex>surfeit</qex> made.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Fullness and oppression of the system, occasioned
often by excessive eating and drinking.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>To prevent <qex>surfeit</qex> and other diseases that are incident
to those that heat their blood by travels.</q>
<rj><qau>Bunyan.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>Disgust caused by excess; satiety.</def> <rj><au>Sir
P. Sidney.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Matter and argument have been supplied abundantly, and even to
<qex>surfeit</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>Burke.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surfeit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Surfeit
<hw>Sur"feit</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To load the stomach
with food, so that sickness or uneasiness ensues; to eat to
excess.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>They are as sick that <qex>surfeit</qex> with too much as they
that starve with nothing.</q> <rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To indulge to satiety in any
gratification.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surfeit</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Surfeit
<hw>Sur"feit</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Surfeited</conjf>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Surfeiting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To feed so as to
oppress the stomach and derange the function of the system; to overfeed,
and produce satiety, sickness, or uneasiness; -- often reflexive;
<as>as, to <ex>surfeit</ex> one's self with sweets</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To fill to satiety and disgust; to cloy; <as>as, he
<ex>surfeits</ex> us with compliments</as>.</def> <rj><au>V.
Knox.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Surfeiter</ent>⟦br⟧
